Early Life and Education:
	•Born on October 17, 1956, in Decatur, Alabama, Mae Jemison is the youngest child of Charlie and Dorothy Jemison.
	- At age three, her family relocated to Chicago, Illinois, seeking better educational opportunities.
	- Growing up she was always on the honor roll and graduated in 1973 when she was 16 years old from high school. 
	• She graduated from Stanford University in 1977 with a Bachelor of Science degree in chemical engineering.
	- Bachelor of Arts degree in African American studies.
	• After graduating from Stanford University, Jemison continued her education and attended Cornell University Medical College where she earned her Doctor of Medicine degree in 1981.
	- After graduating from medical school, she interned at the Los Angeles County Medical Center and later practiced general medicine.

Medical Career:
	• Dr.Jemison interned at Los Angeles County/University of Southern California Medical Center and worked as a general practitioner.

	• From January 1983 to mid-1985, Jemison served as the area Peace Corps medical officer for Sierra Leone and Liberia, where she also conducted medical research on various projects.
	- “On call twenty four hours a day, seven days a week for two and a half years, in a place that could be so unforgiving of mistakes, I gained flexibility, knowledge, interpersonal relationship skills, and an appreciation of the challenges life poses to so many people on this planet … The insights I gained into the misconceptions of lifestyles and the challenges and opportunities in poor countries nourished my imagination. I understood. What we decide to do with our talents is up to each one of us and is based on our view of life and our desires” 

NASA Career:	
	• In October 1985, Jemison applied for NASA’s astronaut training program.
	• Following the Challenger disaster in January 1986, the selection process was delayed, but she reapplied and was selected in June 1987, becoming the first Black woman admitted to the program.
	• On September 12, 1992, Jemison flew into space aboard the Space Shuttle Endeavour on mission STS-47, making her the first Black woman to travel into space.
Post-NASA Endeavors:
	• After leaving NASA in 1993, Jemison founded a company researching the application of technology to daily life.
	• She also became a professor, teaching environmental studies at Dartmouth College and continuing to advocate for science education.
Honors and Recognitions:
	• Jemison has received several awards and honorary doctorates in recognition of her contributions to science and space exploration.

Dr. Mae Jemison’s groundbreaking achievements continue to inspire future generations in the fields of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM).


